    <a href="/reading/cognitive-science/" class="text-sm mb-4 inline-block">&larr; back to cognitive science</a>

    <h1>Cognitive Architecture</h1>
    <p class="text-gray-400 text-sm mb-6">Lovelace textbook &middot; CC BY-SA 4.0 &middot; <a href="https://computationalcognitivescience.github.io/lovelace/home">computationalcognitivescience.github.io/lovelace/home</a></p>

    <div class="bg-zinc-800 rounded-lg p-5 mb-8 callout">
      <p class="text-lg" style="max-width:none">A <strong>cognitive architecture</strong> is a fixed computational infrastructure within which knowledge and skills operate. <strong>ACT-R</strong> and <strong>Soar</strong> are the two most influential architectures. Both use <strong>production rules</strong> (if-then rules that fire on working memory contents) as their central mechanism. The question is not which module does what, but how the modules compose into a unified system that perceives, remembers, decides, and acts. <a href="https://june.kim/the-natural-framework"><img src="/reading/jk.png" alt="jk" style="display:inline;height:1em;vertical-align:-0.1em;margin-right:0.2em;"/>The Natural Framework</a> decomposes this into six functional roles.</p>
    </div>

    <!-- Production systems -->
    <h3>Production systems</h3>
    <p>A production system has three parts: a <strong>working memory</strong> that holds the current situation, a set of <strong>production rules</strong> (condition-action pairs), and a <strong>conflict resolution</strong> mechanism that selects which rule fires when multiple rules match. The cycle repeats: match rules against working memory, select one, fire it, update working memory.</p>

    <!-- SVG: perception/memory/action architecture -->
